# Nuages Dashboard Specification

## 1. Product Vision

Nuages Dashboard is a React single-page application (SPA) that provides a modern, visual control plane for Nuages operations over WebSocket, with functional parity to Nuages CLI and usability optimized for managing many implants and concurrent operations.

Primary outcome: users can perform all daily operator workflows currently done in CLI (and existing WebCli) through an intuitive, tabbed dashboard without sacrificing speed, observability, or control.

## 2. Scope

### 2.1 In Scope (MVP)

- Server selection and connection profile management.
- Login/authentication against Nuages server.
- Real-time implant management (list, inspect, select, kill, configure).
- Workspace tabs for core areas (Implants, Jobs, Files, Modules, Handlers, Listeners, Tunnels, Channels, Webhooks, Settings).
- Multi-session tab model for implant-focused and job-focused workflows.
- File system explorer per implant with path-aware caching.
- Real-time updates via WebSocket (Socket.IO + Feathers services).
- Command/job execution and result inspection.

### 2.2 Out of Scope (Initial MVP)

- Multi-user collaboration in the same browser session.
- Full offline operation.
- Replacing every low-level terminal interaction day 1.
- Mobile-native app (responsive web only).

## 3. Feature Parity Targets (CLI to Dashboard)

Dashboard should cover all main command domains currently exposed by Nuages CLI:

- Authentication: `!login`
- Implants and interaction: `!implants`, `!implant`, `!shell`, `!interactive`, `!config`
- File workflows: `!files`, `!put`, `!get`
- Modules and execution: `!use`, `!modules`, `!run`, `!autoruns`
- Infrastructure: `!handlers`, `!listeners`, `!tunnels`, `!channels`, `!webhooks`
- Operations and state: `!jobs`, `!options`, `!set`, `!unset`, `!back`

## 4. UX and Visual Direction

### 4.1 Experience Principles

- Dense but readable: prioritize operational clarity over marketing-style whitespace.
- Real-time confidence: status changes should feel immediate and explicit.
- Progressive disclosure: keep advanced options available but not noisy.
- Parallel work: users can manage many implants/jobs at once.

### 4.2 Visual System

- A bold command-center style with strong typography, high-contrast surfaces, and clear state color semantics.
- Distinct semantic color tokens:
	- Healthy/online
	- Warning/stale
	- Error/failed
	- Active/focused
- Subtle animated transitions for:
	- Tab creation/activation
	- New job result arrival
	- Implant heartbeat changes

### 4.3 Responsive Behavior

- Desktop-first, supports down to tablet and narrow laptop widths.
- On small widths, side panels collapse into drawers while maintaining tab/session workflows.

